Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Vector quantization - Clustering colours", "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.779271454538445*^9, 3.779271501947041*^9}, {
  3.779282582810024*^9, 
  3.779282587645894*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8107bb5c-8385-4662-bb94-\
f498d005b5a7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Data clustering can be used to reduce information in datasets while keeping \
essential features. For instance, given an image, one can group pixels in ",
 StyleBox["K",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " clusters of similar colour and represent each pixel by the centre of the \
cluster it belongs to. This reduces the space requirements to store the image \
since the color of the centre of clusters repeats many times and, instead of \
storing them many times, we can store them once and then create pointers to \
them. In this way, vector quantization can be viewed as lossy compression \
method. \n\nHere, the steps for vector quantization are illustrated using the \
following image (found with Google as free to use, share or modify, even \
commercially, see https://images.app.goo.gl/ucLpBjMSTEepMpug9):"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.779283072054423*^9, 3.779283098198203*^9}, {
  3.779283160197457*^9, 3.779283185028699*^9}, {3.7792832419145536`*^9, 
  3.779283437811179*^9}, {3.779351790352479*^9, 3.779351822246218*^9}, {
  3.779351949627554*^9, 3.779351963269543*^9}, {3.779354080500284*^9, 
  3.7793541094136353`*^9}, {3.779355167855635*^9, 3.779355195332465*^9}, {
  3.7819412033471007`*^9, 3.7819412208990555`*^9}, {3.78194168405556*^9, 
  3.781941704695082*^9}, {3.781941761209579*^9, 3.78194202782251*^9}, {
  3.78194231725488*^9, 3.781942332002721*^9}, {3.7819423626923933`*^9, 
  3.781942371636019*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2bada72e-2004-417d-a011-\
